WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:16.910
&gt;&gt; Robert Casper:
Hello everyone.

00:00:16.910 --> 00:00:22.060
Thanks for coming out on
a rainy Tuesday afternoon.

00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:23.860
My name is Rob Casper.

00:00:23.860 --> 00:00:26.160
I'm the head of the Poetry
and Literature Center here

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:27.630
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:31.210
And I'm delighted to welcome
you to our kick-off event.

00:00:31.210 --> 00:00:33.970
What is, what was, what
is, and what will be.

00:00:33.970 --> 00:00:36.880
A cross-genre look
at Afrofuturism.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:40.320
Part of Celebration of
Afrofuturism that will go

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:42.280
into the evening and
across the street.

00:00:42.280 --> 00:00:46.050
Over to the Folger
Shakespeare Library.

00:00:46.050 --> 00:00:48.330
Before I go further, let
me tell you a little bit

00:00:48.330 --> 00:00:50.200
about the Poetry and
Literature Center

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:52.350
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:52.350 --> 00:00:55.110
The Center is home to the
Poet Laureate and Poet-- .

00:00:55.110 --> 00:00:57.420
Poet Laureate Consultant
in Poetry.

00:00:57.420 --> 00:00:59.310
The only federally-funded
position

00:00:59.310 --> 00:01:02.350
for a literary artist
in this country.

00:01:02.350 --> 00:01:07.350
It also hosts, hosts a range
of programs such as this one,

00:01:07.350 --> 00:01:08.900
mostly here at the library.

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:12.120
But also at the Hill
Center and around town.

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:14.140
And really, around the country.

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:17.530
If you want to find out
more about our programs,

00:01:17.530 --> 00:01:22.820
you can go to our website,
www.LOC.gov/poetry.

00:01:22.820 --> 00:01:24.790
You can also sign
the sign-up sheet

00:01:24.790 --> 00:01:26.400
which is outside in the foyer.

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:29.550
And we have surveys
on the chairs.

00:01:29.550 --> 00:01:31.270
We'd love to have
you fill them out.

00:01:31.270 --> 00:01:32.880
I'll remind you at the
end of the program.

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:34.620
But please do so.

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:35.920
You can hand them to me.

00:01:35.920 --> 00:01:37.220
You can leave them on the seats.

00:01:37.220 --> 00:01:38.520
You can leave them on the table.

00:01:38.520 --> 00:01:40.980
Wherever you leave them, we
will find them and report

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:43.410
on what you have to say.

00:01:43.410 --> 00:01:48.140
It seem like eons ago when
dear Teri Cross Davis,

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:50.800
the force behind the
Folger Shakespeare Library's

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:54.870
[inaudible] Poetry Series
contacted our office

00:01:54.870 --> 00:01:57.850
with the idea of
celebrating Afrofuturism.

00:01:57.850 --> 00:02:00.870
And for those of you who
now Teri, that's no surprise

00:02:00.870 --> 00:02:03.430
that she had a visionary
plan in mind.

00:02:03.430 --> 00:02:05.090
As she often does.

00:02:05.090 --> 00:02:07.870
Much thanks to Teri,
who's been so much fun

00:02:07.870 --> 00:02:10.380
to work with over the years.

00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:11.900
For all that you've done.

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:14.320
For all your behind-the-scenes
work to make this happen.

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:15.740
There was a lot of negotiating,

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:17.320
figuring out and
what made sense.

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:18.620
And how we were going to do it.

00:02:18.620 --> 00:02:22.220
And I couldn't be happier
at what we have in store

00:02:22.220 --> 00:02:25.190
for us this afternoon
and this evening.

00:02:25.190 --> 00:02:29.610
As I said, there's an
event at 7:30PM just

00:02:29.610 --> 00:02:30.910
down the street at the Folger.

00:02:30.910 --> 00:02:34.330
Featuring our presenters.

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:37.080
You should note that
advance tickets are sold out.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:41.710
But especially because the
weather is not so great,

00:02:41.710 --> 00:02:44.410
there'll be a standby line.

00:02:44.410 --> 00:02:47.940
And when tickets, should
they become available,

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:49.240
you can pick them up.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:51.520
That stand, standby
line starts at 6:30PM.

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:55.330
So if you don't have
tickets, I'd say try your luck

00:02:55.330 --> 00:02:58.450
and hopefully your
luck will be good.

00:02:58.450 --> 00:03:02.420
I also want to thank our,
our other presenting partner,

00:03:02.420 --> 00:03:04.520
the PEN/Faulkner Foundation.

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:05.990
And in particular Programs

00:03:05.990 --> 00:03:08.460
and Logistics Director,
Shahenda Helmy.

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:09.760
Where is she?

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:11.060
There she is.

00:03:11.060 --> 00:03:14.790
Thanks, Shahenda for all that
you did making this happen.

00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:17.290
I'm very excited now

00:03:17.290 --> 00:03:22.080
to introduce the foundation's
new Executive Director,

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:24.510
Gwydion Suilebhan.

00:03:24.510 --> 00:03:34.530
[ Applause ]

00:03:34.530 --> 00:03:36.080
&gt;&gt; Gwydion Suilebhan:
Hi, everybody!

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:38.230
Nice to see you all.

00:03:38.230 --> 00:03:40.190
Yeah, the rain did
not stop this crowd.

00:03:40.190 --> 00:03:41.490
That's great.

00:03:41.490 --> 00:03:45.240
My sincere thanks to the Library
of Congress and to the Folger

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:46.540
for making everything happen.

00:03:46.540 --> 00:03:47.840
We are really honored

00:03:47.840 --> 00:03:50.290
to be partnered tonight,
today and tonight.

00:03:50.290 --> 00:03:55.070
At, at PEN/Faulkner, we
work to ensure that stories

00:03:55.070 --> 00:03:58.380
and storytellers of
all ages flourish.

00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:01.460
Both in D.C. and all
over the country.

00:04:01.460 --> 00:04:04.360
We give out the PEN/Faulkner
Award for Fiction,

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:07.530
one of the top three literary
prizes in the United States.

00:04:07.530 --> 00:04:10.970
And the PEN/Malamud Award
for the short story.

00:04:10.970 --> 00:04:14.810
We, also here in D.C., we, our
Writers in Schools program.

00:04:14.810 --> 00:04:18.470
We bring free books and
authors into D.C. public

00:04:18.470 --> 00:04:22.010
and public charter schools to
inspire the next generation

00:04:22.010 --> 00:04:23.880
of readers and writers.

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:26.820
And then we also host
events like this one.

00:04:26.820 --> 00:04:29.730
In which we invite
writers to help us.

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:32.580
In the words of the
great performance artist

00:04:32.580 --> 00:04:33.880
and playwright Taylor Mac,

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:36.230
to help us "dream
the culture forward."

00:04:36.230 --> 00:04:38.510
We're going to be hearing

00:04:38.510 --> 00:04:40.900
from three very inspiring
artists tonight.

00:04:40.900 --> 00:04:44.960
And the conversation they
kick off will be incomplete.

00:04:44.960 --> 00:04:47.810
Unless you all help us
carry it forward from here.

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:51.510
So ask questions during the Q&amp;A.

00:04:51.510 --> 00:04:54.680
Talk about what we
hear tonight, today.

00:04:54.680 --> 00:04:55.980
With the people you
came here with.

00:04:55.980 --> 00:04:57.510
And better yet, talk about it

00:04:57.510 --> 00:05:00.800
with the people you're sitting
next to who you don't know.

00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:02.900
Let's make it a robust
conversation

00:05:02.900 --> 00:05:04.930
that leaves this room.

00:05:04.930 --> 00:05:07.230
And goes out into the world.

00:05:07.230 --> 00:05:11.250
So now I want to introduce
tonight's moderator.

00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:13.660
Or today's moderator,
Sheree Renee Thomas.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:15.100
Thomas, thank you.

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:18.030
She's an award-winning
fiction writer, poet, editor,

00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:22.170
and her worth is, work is
inspired by myth and folklore.

00:05:22.170 --> 00:05:24.660
By natural science and conjure.

00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:27.560
Her roots in Memphis and
the genius culture created

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:29.660
in the Mississippi Delta.

00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:32.510
Thank you so much,
Sheree, and welcome.

00:05:32.510 --> 00:05:40.090
[ Applause ]

00:05:40.090 --> 00:05:41.390
&gt;&gt; Sheree Renee Thomas:
Thank you.

00:05:41.390 --> 00:05:42.690
It's so wonderful to be here.

00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:45.230
And thank you to Teri
who is a fellow poet.

00:05:45.230 --> 00:05:48.300
And a magic woman,
in her own rights.

00:05:48.300 --> 00:05:49.600
So thank you so much.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:53.490
I am honored to introduce
these fabulous writers.

00:05:53.490 --> 00:05:55.990
This is a cross-genre
conversation

00:05:55.990 --> 00:05:57.490
that we're going to have.

00:05:57.490 --> 00:06:00.760
These writers write
science fiction, fantasy.

00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:03.450
They write horror,
they write in stories,

00:06:03.450 --> 00:06:06.690
they write novels,
and they write poems.

00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:10.420
And new forms that we haven't
quite given a name to, as well.

00:06:10.420 --> 00:06:15.510
So the first writer I'm going
to introduce is Tananarive Due.

00:06:15.510 --> 00:06:27.040
[ Applause ]

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:30.660
Tananarive Due is an author,
screenwriter, and educator

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:31.960
who is the leading voice

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:33.840
in black speculative
fiction and in horror.

00:06:33.840 --> 00:06:36.440
Her short fiction has appeared
in the Best of Year Anthology

00:06:36.440 --> 00:06:37.920
of Science Fiction and Fantasy.

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:39.520
Almost every single year.

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:41.970
She is the former
Distinguished Visiting Lecturer

00:06:41.970 --> 00:06:43.270
at Spelman College.

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:46.550
And she teaches Afrofuturism and
Black Horror in the Department

00:06:46.550 --> 00:06:49.470
of African American
Studies at UCLA.

00:06:49.470 --> 00:06:52.190
She also teaches in the
Creative Writing MFA Program

00:06:52.190 --> 00:06:54.420
at Antioch University,
Los Angeles.

00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:56.180
And in their Screenwriting
program,

00:06:56.180 --> 00:06:57.570
as well as Santa Barbara.

00:06:57.570 --> 00:06:59.280
And she had the great
distinct honor

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:02.650
of having Jordan
Peele visit her class.

00:07:02.650 --> 00:07:04.350
Which she documented as well.

00:07:04.350 --> 00:07:05.650
You can see that online.

00:07:05.650 --> 00:07:06.950
It was amazing.

00:07:06.950 --> 00:07:09.780
Due is an executive
producer of Shutter.

00:07:09.780 --> 00:07:12.660
Which has a wonderful new
black horror documentary called

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:13.960
Horror Noire.

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:16.150
It debuted, The Streaming
Network

00:07:16.150 --> 00:07:17.740
on February the seventh, right?

00:07:17.740 --> 00:07:21.200
So you need to subscribe and
check it out immediately.

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:23.140
She is the American
Book Award winner

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:25.860
and NAACP Image Award recipient.

00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:29.350
And then author or co-author
of at least a dozen novels.

00:07:29.350 --> 00:07:31.360
She's working on some
new work as well.

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:34.700
In 2010 she was inducted
into the Medill School

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:36.210
of Journalism's Hall
of Achievement

00:07:36.210 --> 00:07:37.950
at Northwestern University.

00:07:37.950 --> 00:07:40.150
She also received a
Lifetime Achievement Award

00:07:40.150 --> 00:07:41.830
in the Fine Arts from
the Congressional Black

00:07:41.830 --> 00:07:43.130
Caucus Foundation.

00:07:43.130 --> 00:07:45.770
And her short story collection,
Ghost Summer, Ghost Summer,

00:07:45.770 --> 00:07:47.930
which you can see right
over there on the table.

00:07:47.930 --> 00:07:50.750
Won a 2016 British
Fantasy Award.

00:07:50.750 --> 00:07:52.810
She has been named to
the [inaudible] 100,

00:07:52.810 --> 00:07:55.370
and to the Ebony Power 100.

00:07:55.370 --> 00:07:58.530
Due also co-authored
a Civil Rights Memoir

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:01.530
with her late mother,
Mrs. Patricia Stevens Due.

00:08:01.530 --> 00:08:04.880
It was called Freedom in the
Family: A mother/daughter memoir

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:06.770
of the fight for civil rights.

00:08:06.770 --> 00:08:08.850
Patricia Stephens
Due is historic.

00:08:08.850 --> 00:08:11.600
Because she took part in
the nation's first jail-in

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:13.480
which happened in 1960.

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:17.930
And she spent 49 days in
jail in Tallahassee Florida.

00:08:17.930 --> 00:08:21.300
And this was after a sit-in at
the Woolworth Lunch Counter.

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:25.320
Freedom in the Family was named
2003's Best Civil Rights Memoir

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:27.010
by Black Issues Book Review.

00:08:27.010 --> 00:08:29.980
Her parents, including her
father, attorney John Due.

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:32.760
Were recently inducted into
the Florida Civil Rights Hall

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:34.060
of Fame.

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:36.140
So she comes from
an amazing family.

00:08:36.140 --> 00:08:41.170
IN 2013, Due co-produced a
short horror film: Danger Word.

00:08:41.170 --> 00:08:44.800
With her husband Steven Barnes
and director Luchina Fisher.

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:47.820
Due and her husband, science
fiction pioneer Steven Barnes,

00:08:47.820 --> 00:08:49.800
also co-wrote The
Short which was based

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:51.180
on their novel, Devil's Wake.

00:08:51.180 --> 00:08:54.400
It starred Frankie Faison
from The Wire, of course.

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:57.830
And Silence of the
Lambs, and Saoirse Scott.

00:08:57.830 --> 00:09:00.730
Danger Word was nominated
for Best Narrative Short

00:09:00.730 --> 00:09:03.660
at the [inaudible] and Pan
African Film Festivals.

00:09:03.660 --> 00:09:05.250
Due has also collaborated

00:09:05.250 --> 00:09:07.760
on the Tennyson Hardwick
mystery series with Barnes.

00:09:07.760 --> 00:09:09.110
And in partnership
with the actor

00:09:09.110 --> 00:09:11.040
and author, Blair Underwood.

00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:13.310
Due also wrote a historical
novel about the life

00:09:13.310 --> 00:09:15.440
of Madame C.J. Walker,
The Black Rose.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:18.310
Which was based on the
research by Alex Haley.

00:09:18.310 --> 00:09:21.240
She has a B.S. in Journalism
from Northwestern University

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:22.820
and an M.A. in English
Literature

00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:24.810
from the University
of Leeds, England.

00:09:24.810 --> 00:09:26.360
That is Tananarive Due.

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:28.510
Thank you.

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:34.320
[ Applause ]

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:36.980
Our next author is Nora Jemisin.

00:09:36.980 --> 00:09:40.510
Her pen name is N.K. Jemisin.

00:09:40.510 --> 00:09:49.490
[ Applause ]

00:09:49.490 --> 00:09:52.970
N.K. Jemisin, Nora is the first
author in the genre's history

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:54.880
to win not one, not two,

00:09:54.880 --> 00:09:58.060
but three consecutive
Best Novel Hugo Awards.

00:09:58.060 --> 00:10:00.950
And all of them for her
Broken Earth Trilogy.

00:10:00.950 --> 00:10:03.750
Her work has also won the
Nebula, the Locus Award,

00:10:03.750 --> 00:10:05.680
and the Good Reads
Choice Awards.

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:07.930
Her speculative works
range from fantasy

00:10:07.930 --> 00:10:10.290
to science fiction,
to the undefinable.

00:10:10.290 --> 00:10:14.340
Her themes include resistance to
oppression, the inseverability

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:18.790
of the liminal, and the
coolness of stuff blowing up.

00:10:18.790 --> 00:10:20.090
[Laughter] She is
currently a review

00:10:20.090 --> 00:10:22.120
for the New York
Times Book Review.

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:24.080
And she has been an
instructor for the Clarion

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:26.860
and Clarion West
Writing Workshops.

00:10:26.860 --> 00:10:29.490
In her spare time, she is
a gamer and a gardener.

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:32.190
And she's also single-handedly
responsible for saving

00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:36.390
from King Ozymandias, Ozzie.

00:10:36.390 --> 00:10:38.950
Her dangerously intelligent
ginger cat.

00:10:38.950 --> 00:10:42.410
And his phenomenally
destructive sidekick, Magpie.

00:10:42.410 --> 00:10:45.880
Magpie. Her essays and fiction
excerpts are available of course

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:50.550
on her website, NKJemisin.com.

00:10:50.550 --> 00:10:52.350
That's Nora.

00:10:52.350 --> 00:10:58.040
[ Applause ]

00:10:58.040 --> 00:11:02.510
Our wonderful poet
is Airea D Matthews.

00:11:02.510 --> 00:11:09.050
[ Applause ]

00:11:09.050 --> 00:11:10.560
Airea D Matthews is the author

00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:12.720
of the poetry collection
Simulacra.

00:11:12.720 --> 00:11:15.970
I knew I was going to
do that: Simulacra.

00:11:15.970 --> 00:11:20.810
One of the 2016 Yale Year
Series of Younger Poets Prize.

00:11:20.810 --> 00:11:23.860
The New Yorker has described
her work as , "Fugues,

00:11:23.860 --> 00:11:25.720
text messages to the dead.

00:11:25.720 --> 00:11:30.290
Imagined outtakes from
Wittgenstein, tart mini operas.

00:11:30.290 --> 00:11:31.650
Fairy tales.

00:11:31.650 --> 00:11:37.010
Matthews' virtuosic, frantic,
and darkly, very darkly funny."

00:11:37.010 --> 00:11:40.610
Matthews' work has appeared in
Callaloo, Best American Poets,

00:11:40.610 --> 00:11:44.210
Harvard Review, American Poet,
and in many other places.

00:11:44.210 --> 00:11:48.050
She was awarded a 2016 Rona
Jaffe Writer's Foundation Award.

00:11:48.050 --> 00:11:51.320
The 2016 Louis Untermeyer
Scholarship

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:53.420
from Bread Loaf Writers'
Conference.

00:11:53.420 --> 00:11:57.700
And a 2015 Kresge Literary Arts
award as well as fellowships

00:11:57.700 --> 00:11:59.510
from Cave Canem Foundation.

00:11:59.510 --> 00:12:02.010
Callaloo, and the
James Merrill House.

00:12:02.010 --> 00:12:06.880
Her current projects include
a second book, Underclass.

00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:10.800
Which seeks to lyrically
deconstruct the accepted

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:13.290
narratives around
poverty and class.

00:12:13.290 --> 00:12:15.870
She is an assistant
professor at Bryn Mawr College

00:12:15.870 --> 00:12:18.480
where she directs the
creative writing program.

00:12:18.480 --> 00:12:21.510
That is Airea D. Matthews.

00:12:21.510 --> 00:12:37.040
[ Applause ]

00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:38.400
&gt;&gt; Sheree Renee Thomas: So our
conversation today is going

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:40.140
to be about a field of work

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:42.510
which seems new to
lots of people.

00:12:42.510 --> 00:12:46.950
But has been evolving since,
basically since we've come

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:49.090
through the Middle Passage.

00:12:49.090 --> 00:12:51.220
Since we, I mean,
literally it has.

00:12:51.220 --> 00:12:55.650
[Laughter] It's a part of, it's
a body of work that has come

00:12:55.650 --> 00:12:58.220
out of colonialism,

00:12:58.220 --> 00:13:01.050
post-colonialism,
neo-colonialism.

00:13:01.050 --> 00:13:07.070
As well as in the African
American experience of slavery.

00:13:07.070 --> 00:13:10.320
And it is now a, a body of work

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:12.320
that have evolved
around the world.

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:15.460
It is global in its
conversation.

00:13:15.460 --> 00:13:16.910
It takes on many, many forms.

00:13:16.910 --> 00:13:19.430
I think of it as
a moveable feast.

00:13:19.430 --> 00:13:21.100
A moveable feast in
which there are lots

00:13:21.100 --> 00:13:23.360
of different afrofutures.

00:13:23.360 --> 00:13:26.050
And one of the things I
would love for us to talk

00:13:26.050 --> 00:13:30.930
about today is what is each
author's experience of the word?

00:13:30.930 --> 00:13:34.420
Because I wouldn't assume that
everyone embraces it equally.

00:13:34.420 --> 00:13:37.510
Because there are a lot
of spaces it covers.

00:13:37.510 --> 00:13:41.210
And in some spaces that it
leaves, unseen and invisible.

00:13:41.210 --> 00:13:42.890
That we still have to explore.

00:13:42.890 --> 00:13:45.160
So we just want to take each
author and have a chance

00:13:45.160 --> 00:13:48.800
to describe what Afrofuturism
is or is not to them.

00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:52.380
&gt;&gt; Would you like me to start?

00:13:52.380 --> 00:13:55.140
I view Afrofuturism, borrowing

00:13:55.140 --> 00:13:59.800
from Alandrine Nelson's
essay some time ago.

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:04.050
Where she talked about the
ontology of multiplicity.

00:14:04.050 --> 00:14:08.370
And I believe that as we
kind of consider afrofutures,

00:14:08.370 --> 00:14:12.880
the black body, both
in present-future-past.

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:15.730
We have to consider
the ways in which we

00:14:15.730 --> 00:14:20.340
as authors can make the
space/time continuum collapse.

00:14:20.340 --> 00:14:23.360
How we can look back,
look forward,

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:25.290
and be present at the same time.

00:14:25.290 --> 00:14:28.050
And I'm very interested in
that inside almost any text.

00:14:28.050 --> 00:14:29.350
It doesn't have to be poetry.

00:14:29.350 --> 00:14:32.290
Any test, prose, poetry.

00:14:32.290 --> 00:14:38.120
How do we think about
identity as something

00:14:38.120 --> 00:14:43.040
that dissolves rather than
something that hardens?

00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:47.620
And Afrofuturism at least for
me allows that opportunity,

00:14:47.620 --> 00:14:49.850
the opportunity to
be many and one.

00:14:49.850 --> 00:14:52.650
The opportunity to
be forward and back.

00:14:52.650 --> 00:14:55.550
And also the opportunity
to think about,

00:14:55.550 --> 00:14:57.400
at least my person, myself.

00:14:57.400 --> 00:15:01.170
As something other
than what currently is.

00:15:01.170 --> 00:15:06.110
The imagination as a powerful
force in, in oppression

00:15:06.110 --> 00:15:09.500
which is what the black
experience in America has been.

00:15:12.370 --> 00:15:15.570
&gt;&gt; That was beautiful.

00:15:15.570 --> 00:15:21.680
[Laughter] Wow .I'm thinking a
lot about how I use Afrofuturism

00:15:21.680 --> 00:15:26.240
in terms of processing
trauma as a horror writer.

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:28.040
And that's something
I got from my mother.

00:15:28.040 --> 00:15:29.930
So I co-signed to all of that.

00:15:29.930 --> 00:15:31.230
So beautifully spoken.

00:15:31.230 --> 00:15:33.210
Yes, that is true.

00:15:33.210 --> 00:15:41.800
That piece of it that most
attracts me is how to take evil

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:43.280
for lack of a better term.

00:15:43.280 --> 00:15:46.000
Interpret evil however you may.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.410
[Laughter] It's very
tempting as we're sitting here

00:15:48.410 --> 00:15:51.620
in Washington, D.C. to be
very specific about it.

00:15:51.620 --> 00:15:53.100
But interpret it as you may.

00:15:53.100 --> 00:15:56.130
But how to take evil
though and, and create sort

00:15:56.130 --> 00:15:59.550
of a fun house, mirror-image
of it.

00:15:59.550 --> 00:16:02.400
That is not the thing itself.

00:16:02.400 --> 00:16:05.820
But a visual or written
expression of a thing

00:16:05.820 --> 00:16:08.570
that is frightening
or frightful.

00:16:08.570 --> 00:16:11.940
And creating survivors,
you know?

00:16:11.940 --> 00:16:13.770
I think of Octavia
Butler's work,

00:16:13.770 --> 00:16:16.700
and her work is not
largely considered horror.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:19.020
And your work, you know.

00:16:19.020 --> 00:16:21.260
There are -- bad
things happen to people.

00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:25.950
It's not considered horror,
but there are lessons.

00:16:25.950 --> 00:16:27.490
Even in that trauma.

00:16:27.490 --> 00:16:29.310
As we watch characters
undergo trauma.

00:16:29.310 --> 00:16:32.150
It helps us perhaps
[inaudible] our trauma.

00:16:32.150 --> 00:16:34.140
And you mentioned my
mother, Sheree, you know.

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:37.640
She wore dark glasses her whole
life after she was tear-gassed

00:16:37.640 --> 00:16:40.170
in 1960 during a
non-violent march.

00:16:40.170 --> 00:16:44.370
And she was the first
horror-lover in my life.

00:16:44.370 --> 00:16:46.530
So I've really learned,
as I've gotten older

00:16:46.530 --> 00:16:48.790
and my trauma was losing her.

00:16:48.790 --> 00:16:52.290
So I've really learned as
I've gotten older to see

00:16:52.290 --> 00:16:55.560
that aspect of Afrofuturism.

00:16:55.560 --> 00:16:58.180
The aspect of it
that's in the shadows.

00:16:58.180 --> 00:17:01.190
That's poking in the spaces
in the basement, right?

00:17:01.190 --> 00:17:03.950
The things that are frightening
that you don't want to look at.

00:17:03.950 --> 00:17:06.800
That aspect has been
very healing for me.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:09.520
And hopefully is for others.

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:12.270
But I really want to echo
this idea of a conversation

00:17:12.270 --> 00:17:14.400
between the past,
present, and future.

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:17.050
Because that's also something
that's very deeply woven

00:17:17.050 --> 00:17:22.170
within the way I address
trauma in my work.

00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:26.980
&gt;&gt; I am painfully
aware, all of a sudden.

00:17:26.980 --> 00:17:28.700
I am the only non-academic
up here.

00:17:28.700 --> 00:17:32.730
So I don't have anything
super-eloquent to say

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:34.890
about ontologies and so on.

00:17:34.890 --> 00:17:36.710
I'm not even really
sure what that is.

00:17:36.710 --> 00:17:42.470
[Laughter] But, but as, I
guess as a practitioner.

00:17:43.780 --> 00:17:45.460
Which all of us are.

00:17:45.460 --> 00:17:48.120
Which, which everyone who
is living and surviving

00:17:48.120 --> 00:17:52.230
in this country today is a
contributor to Afrofuturism.

00:17:52.230 --> 00:17:56.890
I don't sort of traffic
in labels and names.

00:17:56.890 --> 00:18:00.300
That, for me is a
thing of academics.

00:18:00.300 --> 00:18:02.030
I write what I write.

00:18:02.030 --> 00:18:04.320
People put whatever label
onto that they want.

00:18:04.320 --> 00:18:06.550
And that has happened
throughout my life.

00:18:06.550 --> 00:18:07.930
And sometimes I don't
like those labels,

00:18:07.930 --> 00:18:12.400
and sometimes I just
kind of go with it.

00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:15.500
So to me, Afrofuturism as I grew

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:19.400
up with it was music,
was visual.

00:18:19.400 --> 00:18:22.080
Was, were things
experienced with the senses.

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:24.720
It was not so much,
there were things

00:18:24.720 --> 00:18:27.730
that impacted your
thoughts through visuals

00:18:27.730 --> 00:18:30.470
and through, through ideas.

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:34.460
But not so much kind of
like directly engaging

00:18:34.460 --> 00:18:35.760
with the future.

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:40.220
Not so much directly, a
story set in another world,

00:18:40.220 --> 00:18:43.360
another past, another
life that could have been.

00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:46.270
Parliament Funkadelic
was Afrofuturism.

00:18:46.270 --> 00:18:49.690
Brother From Another Planet.

00:18:49.690 --> 00:18:52.520
These days [inaudible]
is Afrofuturism to me.

00:18:52.520 --> 00:18:55.580
I'm still coming to
a place of acceptance

00:18:55.580 --> 00:18:59.190
that now Afrofuturism
is texted, is textual.

00:18:59.190 --> 00:19:02.740
And I am, I am not
really 100% there yet.

00:19:02.740 --> 00:19:05.360
Because for me, there's,
there's certain power

00:19:05.360 --> 00:19:07.420
in visuals and imagery.

00:19:07.420 --> 00:19:10.170
That I, I know that text can do.

00:19:10.170 --> 00:19:14.310
Since I am not a person
who visualizes my own text.

00:19:14.310 --> 00:19:17.720
It's hard for me to put
those things together.

00:19:17.720 --> 00:19:22.170
So, you know I'm,
I'm accepting it.

00:19:22.170 --> 00:19:25.340
I'm slowly going to
do so at some point.

00:19:25.340 --> 00:19:26.860
Not there yet.

00:19:26.860 --> 00:19:30.600
But I am also deeply and
painfully mindful of the fact

00:19:30.600 --> 00:19:35.870
that once a word reaches Library
of Congress-level mainstream.

00:19:35.870 --> 00:19:40.250
At that point, that word
has transformed beyond its

00:19:40.250 --> 00:19:42.320
intention, its original
intention.

00:19:42.320 --> 00:19:44.310
And maybe is no longer
a useful word.

00:19:44.310 --> 00:19:50.370
So you know because I will
share a simple anecdote.

00:19:50.370 --> 00:19:53.320
Of I got a call from
a production company

00:19:53.320 --> 00:19:55.000
that was interested
in my writing.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:00.180
Something Afrofuturistic,
they said, for, for some film

00:20:00.180 --> 00:20:01.830
that they were going
to do or something.

00:20:01.830 --> 00:20:04.340
And first off then I was like,
"I don't write screenplays.

00:20:04.340 --> 00:20:06.910
I don't know why you called me."

00:20:06.910 --> 00:20:10.230
But anyway, so they,
they asked me to do this.

00:20:10.230 --> 00:20:13.000
And then I was like
well, so what,

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.940
what kind of topic were
you thinking about here?

00:20:15.940 --> 00:20:17.240
And they were like, "Well,
we want something set

00:20:17.240 --> 00:20:18.770
in Africa in the future."

00:20:18.770 --> 00:20:25.120
[Laughter] And I was like, well,
I've never even visited Africa.

00:20:25.120 --> 00:20:30.330
So maybe you might want to find
someone else who's from there.

00:20:30.330 --> 00:20:33.210
You know, there are lots of
writers out there from many

00:20:33.210 --> 00:20:34.520
of the countries in Africa.

00:20:34.520 --> 00:20:36.060
You might want to have
a conversation with them

00:20:36.060 --> 00:20:38.690
about what they would
con-- consider doing.

00:20:38.690 --> 00:20:42.390
But to them, Afrofuturism
was this incredibly limiting

00:20:42.390 --> 00:20:47.350
and super narrow lane that
they wanted me to stay in.

00:20:47.350 --> 00:20:49.770
And I don't drive in that lane.

00:20:49.770 --> 00:20:51.070
I've never been there.

00:20:51.070 --> 00:20:54.080
So, so I'm mindful of the fact

00:20:54.080 --> 00:20:55.490
that maybe we should
start looking

00:20:55.490 --> 00:20:57.090
for the next word to come.

00:20:57.090 --> 00:20:58.790
Maybe Afrofuturism
is not the word

00:20:58.790 --> 00:21:02.060
that we should be
trafficking in anymore.

00:21:02.060 --> 00:21:06.340
But for now, I'll take it.

00:21:06.340 --> 00:21:07.640
&gt;&gt; Sheree Renee Thomas: It's
so interesting that you talk

00:21:07.640 --> 00:21:10.100
about music and other
forms, performing arts,

00:21:10.100 --> 00:21:13.320
visual arts as being
your initial experiences

00:21:13.320 --> 00:21:14.620
with Afrofuturism.

00:21:14.620 --> 00:21:16.790
And how that's really
been a journey for you,

00:21:16.790 --> 00:21:20.310
about text work as Afrofuturism.

00:21:20.310 --> 00:21:21.960
I would say the same
for me as well.

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:25.910
I think one of my earliest
experiences with music as well.

00:21:25.910 --> 00:21:27.660
That I would think
of as Afrofuturism

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:29.740
of course was George Clinton,

00:21:29.740 --> 00:21:33.110
Parliament funk,
all of those things.

00:21:33.110 --> 00:21:36.690
As well as Alice Coltrane and
John Coltrane, their music.

00:21:36.690 --> 00:21:38.930
Sun Ra, of course,
being from the South.

00:21:38.930 --> 00:21:40.230
Was very fascinating to me.

00:21:40.230 --> 00:21:43.630
How does a man, you know
from the Deep South.

00:21:43.630 --> 00:21:46.390
The Bible Belt reimagines
himself

00:21:46.390 --> 00:21:49.530
as an Egyptian god of some sort?

00:21:49.530 --> 00:21:53.620
An alien that's come
to, to the planet.

00:21:53.620 --> 00:21:58.120
When we think about the
experience, the experiences

00:21:58.120 --> 00:22:03.040
with an S, of being black on
the planet, wherever that is.

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:06.360
Whether it's in the America
or on the continent of Africa

00:22:06.360 --> 00:22:08.770
or in, in numerous
places of the,

00:22:08.770 --> 00:22:11.130
other parts of the diaspora.

00:22:11.130 --> 00:22:15.420
You realize that you're
already in a dystopic reality.

00:22:15.420 --> 00:22:17.860
You are already a part of that.

00:22:17.860 --> 00:22:20.020
You know, [inaudible] a
black [inaudible] who wrote

00:22:20.020 --> 00:22:22.840
about this deeply
in the nineties.

00:22:22.840 --> 00:22:26.190
Talked about the first
ships, the first contact,

00:22:26.190 --> 00:22:28.700
close encounter story was of.

00:22:28.700 --> 00:22:31.400
You know us being taken
from our home in Africa.

00:22:31.400 --> 00:22:34.370
And being brought to this other
place for a whole other context.

00:22:34.370 --> 00:22:37.820
And it's sort of an
alien UFO experience.

00:22:37.820 --> 00:22:40.260
And how do you, how do
you write about that.

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:44.950
Airea, I know that you have
been writing poems in the voices

00:22:44.950 --> 00:22:46.940
of Egyptian goddesses.

00:22:46.940 --> 00:22:48.240
You know, how did you come

00:22:48.240 --> 00:22:50.590
to write your Sekhmet,
Sekhmet poems?

00:22:50.590 --> 00:22:53.070
Talk about that.

00:22:53.070 --> 00:22:54.370
&gt;&gt; Airea D. Matthews:
Sekhmet came

00:22:54.370 --> 00:22:56.390
to me actually as I was trying.

00:22:56.390 --> 00:23:00.230
I'm interested in visitations,
like spiritual visitations

00:23:00.230 --> 00:23:01.650
from other things that are.

00:23:01.650 --> 00:23:03.020
May not be in this dimension.

00:23:03.020 --> 00:23:04.410
I know that sounds odd.

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:05.710
But I'm open to it just,

00:23:05.710 --> 00:23:07.380
if it gets to the
writing, I'm open to it.

00:23:07.380 --> 00:23:10.130
So Ann Sexton makes
a show in the,

00:23:10.130 --> 00:23:12.350
in the book as does Sekhmet.

00:23:12.350 --> 00:23:17.060
And I was interested
in what they might have

00:23:17.060 --> 00:23:19.030
to say about the subject.

00:23:19.030 --> 00:23:21.170
As whatever I was
writing about at the time.

00:23:21.170 --> 00:23:25.390
So Sekhmet I'm writing
about addiction.

00:23:25.390 --> 00:23:30.460
And so Sekhmet makes a show
because Sekhmet, they gave her.

00:23:30.460 --> 00:23:33.740
She was going to
destroy a whole army.

00:23:33.740 --> 00:23:37.360
And then these kind of male
gods came forward and like.

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:39.730
"Maybe you can just
give her some liquor."

00:23:39.730 --> 00:23:41.950
They gave her some wine,
thinking and had her believe

00:23:41.950 --> 00:23:43.450
that it was blood
that she was drinking.

00:23:43.450 --> 00:23:45.000
And that would kind
of calm her down.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:47.670
And she would move away
from wanting to destroy.

00:23:47.670 --> 00:23:50.580
And I just kind of thought
about all the ways that we try

00:23:50.580 --> 00:23:55.130
to calm, try to calm
our natural natures.

00:23:55.130 --> 00:23:59.130
Try to house our natural
natures inside of something

00:23:59.130 --> 00:24:01.240
that is not what we want.

00:24:01.240 --> 00:24:03.010
So someone offers you something

00:24:03.010 --> 00:24:06.010
that is not exactly what you
want, but you take it anyway.

00:24:06.010 --> 00:24:07.720
And so Sekhmet came
to fore for me.

00:24:07.720 --> 00:24:10.380
I started thinking about what it
is that she had to go through.

00:24:10.380 --> 00:24:12.780
How she, she was probably.

00:24:12.780 --> 00:24:17.730
They have documented in
myth that she drank a lot.

00:24:17.730 --> 00:24:21.160
And so as did her revelers
and her worshippers.

00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:22.990
And so I was interested in that,

00:24:22.990 --> 00:24:24.590
and how do you get
that story out?

00:24:24.590 --> 00:24:26.510
We have convenient myths.

00:24:26.510 --> 00:24:28.240
There are things
we want to remember

00:24:28.240 --> 00:24:30.940
about these mythologies
that we follow.

00:24:30.940 --> 00:24:34.150
But we don't actually
get down to the root

00:24:34.150 --> 00:24:35.570
of the story of the myth.

00:24:35.570 --> 00:24:38.240
Like what was the very
human nature of the god?

00:24:38.240 --> 00:24:42.430
What was the very human nature
of the entity that makes itself,

00:24:42.430 --> 00:24:44.230
[inaudible] itself in
any kind of mythology.

00:24:44.230 --> 00:24:47.920
Whether it's Greek mythology
or if it's Egyptian mythology.

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:51.360
They're told in, in order

00:24:51.360 --> 00:24:53.910
to give us some sort
of lesson from it.

00:24:53.910 --> 00:24:55.820
And we can't get to
the lesson until we get

00:24:55.820 --> 00:24:58.480
to the humanity of
the god itself.

00:24:58.480 --> 00:25:00.690
And so I try to drive for that.

00:25:00.690 --> 00:25:03.940
And I'm interested in
all sorts of mythology.

00:25:03.940 --> 00:25:08.940
But Egyptian mythology does
come to the forefront for me.

00:25:08.940 --> 00:25:11.100
Primarily because
those aren't the myths

00:25:11.100 --> 00:25:13.940
that are typically
told in the West.

00:25:13.940 --> 00:25:15.240
We don't know those myths.

00:25:15.240 --> 00:25:16.730
We know Zeus and Hera.

00:25:16.730 --> 00:25:19.250
But we don't know
about Sekhmet and Ra.

00:25:19.250 --> 00:25:20.600
And why is that?

00:25:20.600 --> 00:25:23.030
So I write about
them because I care.

00:25:23.030 --> 00:25:26.430
I'm trying to make those come
forward a little bit more

00:25:26.430 --> 00:25:27.730
in the work.

00:25:27.730 --> 00:25:29.820
Than have them recede
to the background.

00:25:29.820 --> 00:25:32.620
&gt;&gt; Sheree Renee Thomas: I know
during the Black Arts movement,

00:25:32.620 --> 00:25:37.260
there was a conscious,
deliberate effort by artists,

00:25:37.260 --> 00:25:41.260
[inaudible], Ishmael
Reeve, Sonia Sanchez.

00:25:41.260 --> 00:25:45.440
Other artists like Alice Walker,
to go back and reclaim some

00:25:45.440 --> 00:25:46.810
of the mythologies of the world.

00:25:46.810 --> 00:25:48.750
And also tell our folk tales.

00:25:48.750 --> 00:25:50.050
Our stories as well.

00:25:50.050 --> 00:25:53.530
And give them the same type
of seriousness that Greek

00:25:53.530 --> 00:25:56.140
and Roman mythology
had been taken.

00:25:56.140 --> 00:25:59.950
Would you say that this effort
that, that's happening now.

00:25:59.950 --> 00:26:01.860
That we're seeing, in the body

00:26:01.860 --> 00:26:03.280
of work we're calling
Afrofuturism.

00:26:03.280 --> 00:26:04.580
For want of other
words, [laughter].

00:26:04.580 --> 00:26:08.400
Is also a continuation of that?

00:26:08.400 --> 00:26:11.690
But it's almost like a
[inaudible] experience.

00:26:11.690 --> 00:26:13.070
Where you're looking.

00:26:13.070 --> 00:26:14.970
You're trying to understand
where we are right now.

00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:17.230
By looking at that
past and claiming it.

00:26:17.230 --> 00:26:19.950
To talk about where we possibly
want to go for the future?

00:26:19.950 --> 00:26:21.250
&gt;&gt; Airea D. Matthews
: Absolutely.

00:26:21.250 --> 00:26:23.180
I mean, and the other thing
that I think people tend to look

00:26:23.180 --> 00:26:26.030
for is they try to look
for representation.

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:28.430
I think it's important
to have representation.

00:26:28.430 --> 00:26:31.140
And if you can find those
African mythologies,

00:26:31.140 --> 00:26:33.650
or the African philosophies
that cater

00:26:33.650 --> 00:26:36.070
to what it is you're
interested in writing about.

00:26:36.070 --> 00:26:38.520
You can see a mirror
in some way.

00:26:38.520 --> 00:26:39.900
What you were talking
about earlier,

00:26:39.900 --> 00:26:41.200
earlier with the mirror.

00:26:41.200 --> 00:26:43.800
How important it is to see some
sort of reflection of yourself.

00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:45.380
I could see a reflection

00:26:45.380 --> 00:26:47.360
of myself inside of
the Egyptian myth.

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:49.940
I don't necessarily
see a reflection

00:26:49.940 --> 00:26:51.580
of myself inside of other myths.

00:26:51.580 --> 00:26:53.650
I see other people
inside those myths.

00:26:53.650 --> 00:26:57.040
But they always feel
outside of my experience.

00:26:57.040 --> 00:27:01.160
I do try and dig a little
deeper and find where I can.

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:04.230
The myths that are
important to me.

00:27:04.230 --> 00:27:06.600
And representative of who I am.

00:27:06.600 --> 00:27:09.300
And what I happen to be
writing about at the moment.

00:27:09.300 --> 00:27:11.190
So yeah, I do believe
that's important.

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:12.520
&gt;&gt; Sheree Renee Thomas: When
